      "\ndef to_nat_digit : Digit → ℕ := fun d ↦ d + 1\ndef is_good_seq {n : ℕ} (s : DigitSeq n) := 10 ∣ ∏a, to_nat_digit (s a)\ndef good_seqs {n : ℕ} := {s : DigitSeq n | is_good_seq s}\n\nnoncomputable determine solution (n : ℕ) : ENNReal :=\n  1 - (8 / 9) ^ n - (5 / 9) ^ n + (4 / 9) ^ n\n\nproblem usa1972_p3 (n : ℕ) (digits : DigitSeq n) :\n  (unifDistN n).toOuterMeasure good_seqs = solution n := sorry\n```\n\nWe need to prove that the probability of a randomly generated sequence of $n$ non-zero digits being divisible by 10 is $1 - \\left(\\frac{8}{9}\\right)^n - \\left(\\frac{5}{9}\\right)^n + \\left(\\frac{4}{9}\\right)^n$.\n\nLet's think about how to approach this proof. We need to show that the outer measure of the set of good sequences (those divisible by 10) with respect to the uniform distribution is equal to the given formula.\n\nFirst, we need to understand what it means for a sequence to be good. A sequence is good if its product is divisible by 10. As we discussed earlier, this means that the sequence must contain at least one even digit (2, 4, 6, 8) and at least one 5.\n\nThe probability of a digit being even is $\\frac{4}{9}$, and the probability of a digit being 5 is $\\frac{1}{9}$. Since the digits are independent, the probability of the sequence being good is the probability that at least one digit is even and at least one digit is 5.\n\nUsing inclusion-exclusion:\n- $P(\\text{Even} \\cup \\text{5}) = P(\\text{Even}) + P(\\text{5}) - P(\\text{Even} \\cap \\text{5})$\n- $P(\\text{Even}) = 1 - \\left(\\frac{5}{9}\\right)^n$ (complement of no evens)\n- $P(\\text{5}) = 1 - \\left(\\frac{8}{9}\\right)^n$ (complement of no 5s)\n- $P(\\text{Even} \\cap \\text{5}) = 1 - \\left(\\frac{5}{9}\\right)^n - \\left(\\frac{8}{9}\\right)^n + \\left(\\frac{4}{9}\\right)^n$ (complement of no evens or no 5s)\n\nSo $P(\\text{Even} \\cup \\text{5}) = \\left(1 - \\left(\\frac{5}{9}\\right)^n\\right) + \\left(1 - \\left(\\frac{8}{9}\\right)^n\\right) - \\left(1 - \\left(\\frac{5}{9}\\right)^n - \\left(\\frac{8}{9}\\right)^n + \\left(\\frac{4}{9}\\right)^n\\right)$\n\nSimplifying: $P(\\text{Even} \\cup \\text{5}) = 1 - \\left(\\frac{5}{9}\\right)^n - \\left(\\frac{8}{9}\\right)^n + \\left(\\frac{4}{9}\\right)^n$\n\nThis matches the formula given in the problem's `solution` definition.\n\nNow, how to prove this in Lean? \n\nWe need to show that the outer measure of the set of good sequences is equal to the given formula. The key insight is that the set of good sequences is precisely the set of sequences that have at least one even digit and at least one 5.\n\nLet's think about how to compute the outer measure. The outer measure of a set with respect to a probability distribution is the sum of the probabilities of the elements in the set. In our case, the distribution is the uniform distribution on the set of all sequences of length $n$.\n\nThe set of all sequences has size $9^n$. The set of good sequences has size equal to the number of sequences with at least one even and at least one 5. \n\nWe can compute the size of the set of good sequences using inclusion-exclusion:\n- Total sequences: $9^n$\n- Sequences with no evens: $5^n$ (only digits 1, 3, 5, 7, 9)\n- Sequences with no 5s: $8^n$ (digits 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 7, 8, 9)\n- Sequences with neither evens nor 5s: $5^n$ (digits 1, 3, 7, 9) - wait, no: if no evens and no 5s, then digits can only be 1, 3, 7, 9 - so 4 choices per digit, so $4^n$ sequences\n\nUsing inclusion-exclusion:\n|A ∪ B| = |A| + |B| - |A ∩ B|\nwhere\n- |A| = number of sequences with no evens = $5^n$\n- |B| = number of sequences with no 5s = $8^n$\n- |A ∩ B| = number of sequences with neither evens nor 5s = $4^n$\n\nSo, the number of sequences that are NOT good is $5^n + 8^n - 4^n$.\n\nTherefore, the number of good sequences is $9^n - (5^n + 8^n - 4^n) = 9^n - 5^n - 8^n + 4^n$.\n\nThe probability is then $\\frac{9^n - 5^n - 8^n + 4^n}{9^n} = 1 - \\frac{5^n}{9^n} - \\frac{8^n}{9^n} + \\frac{4^n}{9^n} = 1 - \\left(\\frac{5}{9}\\right)^n - \\left(\\frac{8}{9}\\right)^n + \\left(\\frac{4}{9}\\right)^n$, which matches the formula.\n\nSo, we need to show that the outer measure of the set of good sequences is equal to this value.\n\nIn Lean, we can compute the outer measure as the sum of the probabilities of the good sequences. Since the distribution is uniform, each sequence has probability $\\frac{1}{9^n}$.\n\nThe set of good sequences has size $9^n - 5^n - 8^n + 4^n$, so the sum of their probabilities is $\\frac{9^n - 5^n - 8^n + 4^n}{9^n} = 1 - \\left(\\frac{5}{9}\\right)^n - \\left(\\frac{8}{9}\\right)^n + \\left(\\frac{4}{9}\\right)^n$.\n\nSo we need to show that the outer measure equals this value. \n\nLet's complete the proof:\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Probability.Distributions.Uniform\n\nimport ProblemExtraction\n\nproblem_file { tags := [.Combinatorics, .NumberTheory] }\n\n/-!\n# USA Mathematical Olympiad 1972, Problem 3\n\nn digits, none of them 0, are randomly (and independently) generated,\nfind the probability that their product is divisible by 10.\n-/\n\nnamespace Usa1972P3\n\nabbrev Digit := Fin 9\nabbrev DigitSeq (n : ℕ) := Fin n → Digit\n\nnoncomputable def unifDistN (n : ℕ) := PMF.uniformOfFintype (DigitSeq n)\n\ndef to_nat_digit : Digit → ℕ := fun d ↦ d + 1\ndef is_good_seq {n : ℕ} (s : DigitSeq n) := 10 ∣ ∏a, to_nat_digit (s a)\ndef good_seqs {n : ℕ} := {s : DigitSeq n | is_good_seq s}\n\nnoncomputable determine solution (n : ℕ) : ENNReal :=\n  1 - (8 / 9) ^ n - (5 / 9) ^ n + (4 / 9) ^ n\n\nproblem usa1972_p3 (n : ℕ) (digits : DigitSeq n) :\n  (unifDistN n).toOuterMeasure good_seqs = solution n := by \n```\n\nWe need to compute the outer measure of the set of good sequences and show it equals the given formula. \n\nFirst, we need to understand what the set of good sequences looks like. A sequence is good if its product is divisible by 10, which means it must contain at least one even digit (2, 4, 6, 8) and at least one 5.\n\nLet's think about how to compute the ou