      "\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Probability.Distributions.Uniform\n\nimport ProblemExtraction\n\nproblem_file { tags := [.Combinatorics, .NumberTheory] }\n\n/-!\n# USA Mathematical Olympiad 1972, Problem 3\n\nn digits, none of them 0, are randomly (and independently) generated,\nfind the probability that their product is divisible by 10.\n-/\n\nnamespace Usa1972P3\n\nabbrev Digit := Fin 9\nabbrev DigitSeq (n : ℕ) := Fin n → Digit\n\nnoncomputable def unifDistN (n : ℕ) := PMF.uniformOfFintype (DigitSeq n)\n\n\ndef to_nat_digit : Digit → ℕ := fun d ↦ d + 1\ndef is_good_seq {n : ℕ} (s : DigitSeq n) := 10 ∣ ∏a, to_nat_digit (s a)\ndef good_seqs {n : ℕ} := {s : DigitSeq n | is_good_seq s}\n\nnoncomputable determine solution (n : ℕ) : ENNReal :=\n  1 - (8 / 9) ^ n - (5 / 9) ^ n + (4 / 9) ^ n\n\nproblem usa1972_p3 (n : ℕ) (digits : DigitSeq n) :\n  (unifDistN n).toOuterMeasure good_seqs = solution n := sorry\n```\n\nWe need to prove that the probability of a sequence of $n$ digits being good (product divisible by 10) is equal to the given solution.\n\nThe approach will be:\n1. Express the probability using the principle of inclusion-exclusion\n2. Calculate the probability of divisibility by 2 and 5 separately\n3. Multiply them since they are independent\n4. Verify the formula is correct\n\nFirst, divisibility by 2: the probability that at least one digit is even. There are 4 even digits (2, 4, 6, 8) and 5 odd digits (1, 3, 5, 7, 9). So the probability that a digit is even is 4/9, and odd is 5/9. The probability that none of the $n$ digits is even (all are odd) is (5/9)^n, so the probability that at least one is even is 1 - (5/9)^n.\n\nNext, divisibility by 5: the probability that at least one digit is 5. There is 1 digit 5 out of 9, so the probability that a digit is 5 is 1/9, and not 5 is 8/9. The probability that none of the $n$ digits is 5 is (8/9)^n, so the probability that at least one is 5 is 1 - (8/9)^n.\n\nThe probability that the product is divisible by 10 is the product of these probabilities (since they are independent): (1 - (5/9)^n) * (1 - (8/9)^n) = 1 - (5/9)^n - (8/9)^n + (4/9)^n. This is exactly the given solution.\n\nSo we need to express this in Lean. The approach will be to:\n1. Unfold the definition of the probability measure\n2. Express the set of good sequences\n3. Compute the measure of this set\n4. Verify it equals the given solution\n\nLet's complete the proof:\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Probability.Distributions.Uniform\n\nimport ProblemExtraction\n\nproblem_file { tags := [.Combinatorics, .NumberTheory] }\n\n/-!\n# USA Mathematical Olympiad 1972, Problem 3\n\nn digits, none of them 0, are randomly (and independently) generated,\nfind the probability that their product is divisible by 10.\n-/\n\nnamespace Usa1972P3\n\nabbrev Digit := Fin 9\nabbrev DigitSeq (n : ℕ) := Fin n → Digit\n\nnoncomputable def unifDistN (n : ℕ) := PMF.uniformOfFintype (DigitSeq n)\n\n\ndef to_nat_digit : Digit → ℕ := fun d ↦ d + 1\ndef is_good_seq {n : ℕ} (s : DigitSeq n) := 10 ∣ ∏a, to_nat_digit (s a)\ndef good_seqs {n : ℕ} := {s : DigitSeq n | is_good_seq s}\n\nnoncomputable determine solution (n : ℕ) : ENNReal :=\n  1 - (8 / 9) ^ n - (5 / 9) ^ n + (4 / 9) ^ n\n\nproblem usa1972_p3 (n : ℕ) (digits : DigitSeq n) :\n  (unifDistN n).toOuterMeasure good_seqs = solution n := by\n```\n\nNow, we need to compute the measure of the set of good sequences. A good sequence is one where the product of the digits is divisible by 10. \n\nWe can compute this probability directly by calculating the probability of divisibility by 2 and 5 separately, and then multiplying them since they are independent.\n\nDivisibility by 2: at least one even digit. The probability that a digit is even is 4/9 (digits 2, 4, 6, 8). So the probability that at least one digit is even is 1 - (5/9)^n (where 5/9 is the probability that a digit is odd).\n\nDivisibility by 5: at least one 5. The probability that a digit is 5 is 1/9, so the probability that at least one