\n\nThese are independent, so we can compute them separately and multiply.\n\nLet's compute the number of sequences where at least one digit is even. Total sequences: 9^n. Number of sequences with all digits odd: 5^n (since each digit has 5 choices). So the number of sequences with at least one even digit is 9^n - 5^n.\n\nSimilarly, the number of sequences with at least one 5: total sequences 9^n, number of sequences with no 5s: 8^n (since each digit has 8 choices). So the number of sequences with at least one 5 is 9^n - 8^n.\n\nWait, these are not independent. So we need to compute the number of sequences where:\n1. At least one even digit\n2. At least one 5\n\nSo the count is the number of sequences with at least one even and at least one 5. So to compute this, we can use inclusion-exclusion:\n\nNumber of sequences with at least one even = 9^n - 5^n\nNumber of sequences with at least one 5 = 9^n - 8^n\nNumber of sequences with at least one even or 5 = (9^n - 5^n) + (9^n - 8^n) - (9^n - 8^n - 5^n + something)\n\nWait, this is getting complicated. Let's think differently.\n\nAlternatively, we can compute the number of sequences where:\n1. At least one even digit\n2. At least one 5\n\nSo to count these, we can compute the number of sequences with at least one even and at least one 5. \n\nSo total sequences: 9^n\nSubtract sequences with no even digits (all odd): 5^n\nSubtract sequences with no 5s: 8^n\nAdd back sequences with no even digits and no 5s: (5^n - (5^n - 0) )? Wait, no.\n\nWait, sequences with no even digits and no 5s: digits must be from {1, 3, 7, 9}, so 4 choices per digit. So number of such sequences: 4^n.\n\nSo by inclusion-exclusion:\nNumber of sequences with at least one even or 5 = 9^n - 4^n.\n\nWait, but we need the number of sequences with at least one even AND at least one 5. \n\nSo we can compute it as:\nTotal sequences - sequences with no even - sequences with no 5 + sequences with neither even nor 5.\n\nWait, this is getting confusing. Let's co