n```\n\nWe define a digit as a value from 0 to 8 (represented as Fin 9), and a sequence of digits of length n as a function from Fin n to Digit.\n\n```tactics\nnoncomputable def unifDistN (n : ℕ) := PMF.uniformOfFintype (DigitSeq n)\n```\n\nThis defines a uniform distribution over all possible sequences of length n.\n\n```tactics\ndef to_nat_digit : Digit → ℕ := fun d ↦ d + 1\ndef is_good_seq {n : ℕ} (s : DigitSeq n) := 10 ∣ ∏a, to_nat_digit (s a)\ndef good_seqs {n : ℕ} := {s : DigitSeq n | is_good_seq s}\n```\n\nWe define a good sequence as one where the product of the digits is divisible by 10. The function `to_nat_digit` converts a Digit (0-8) to a natural number (1-9). The set of good sequences is the collection of all sequences satisfying `is_good_seq`.\n\n```tactics\nnoncomputable determine solution (n : ℕ) : ENNReal :=\n  1 - (8 / 9) ^ n - (5 / 9) ^ n + (4 / 9) ^ n\n```\n\nThis defines the probability solution as the given formula.\n\nNow we need to prove the main theorem.\n\n```tactics\nproblem usa1972_p3 (n : ℕ) (digits : DigitSeq n) :\n  (unifDistN n).toOuterMeasure good_seqs = solution n := sorry\n```\n\nThe theorem statement sets up the goal: prove that the probability of a good sequence under the uniform distribution equals the given solution. The proof is currently a placeholder (`sorry`).\n\nTo complete the proof, we need to:\n1. Show that the set of good sequences has the claimed probability\n2. Use the properties of the uniform distribution\n\nThe key insight is that the probability of a good sequence is the probability that:\n- At least one digit is even (2, 4, 6, 8)\n- At least one digit is 5\n\nThe probability that a digit is even is $4/9$, and the probability it's odd is $5/9$. The probability it's 5 is $1/9$, and not 5 is $8/9$.\n\nThe probability that none of the digits is even is $(5/9)^n$.\nThe probability that none of the digits is 5 is $(8/9)^n$.\n\nThe probability that none of the digits is even or none of the digits is 5 is $(5/9)^n + (8/9)^n - (5/9)^n \\cdot (8/9)^n$ (using inclusion-exclusion).\n\nTherefore, the probability that the product is divisible by 10 is $1 - (5/9)^n - (8/9)^n + (5/9)^n \\cdot (8/9)^n$, which simplifies to the given solution.\n\nTo formalize this in Lean 4, we need to:\n1. Express the probability of a good sequence in terms of the given formula\n2. Use properties of the uniform distribution and probability\n\nWe can approach this by:\n- Showing that the probability of a good sequence is the probability of the union of two independent events\n- Using the formula for the union of two independent events: P(A ∪ B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A ∩ B)\n- Computing each probability\n- Simplifying to the given formula\n\nLet's complete the proof.\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Probability.Distributions.Uniform\n\nimport ProblemExtraction\n\nproblem_file { tags := [.Combinatorics, .NumberTheory] }\n```\n\nNow we define the problem.\n\n```tactics\n/-!\n# USA Mathematical Olympiad 1972, Problem 3\n\nn digits, none of them 0, are randomly (and independently) generated,\nfind the probability that their product is divisible by 10.\n-/\n\nnamespace Usa1972P3\n\nabbrev Digit := Fin 9\nabbrev DigitSeq (n : ℕ) := Fin n → Digit\n```\n\nWe define a digit as a value from 0 to 8 (represented as Fin 9), and a sequence of digits of length n as a function from Fin n to Digit.\n\n```tactics\nnoncomputable def unifDistN (n : ℕ) := PMF.uniformOfFintype (DigitSeq n)\n```\n\nThis defines a uniform distribution over all possible sequences of length n.\n\n```tactics\ndef to_nat_digit : Digit → ℕ := fun d ↦ d + 1\ndef is_good_seq {n : ℕ} (s : DigitSeq n) := 10 ∣ ∏a, to_nat_digit (s a)\ndef good_seqs {n : ℕ} := {s : DigitSeq n | is_good_seq s}\n```\n\nWe define a good sequence as one where the product of the digits is divisible by 10. The function `to_nat_digit` converts a Digit (0-8) to a natural number (1-9). The set of good sequences is the collection of all sequences satisfying `is_good_seq`.\n\n```tactics\nnoncomputable determine solution (n : ℕ) : ENNReal :=\n  1 - (8 / 9) ^ n - (5 / 9) ^ n + (4 / 9) ^ n\n```\n\nThis defines the probability solution as the given formula.\n\nNow we need to prove the main theorem.\n\n```tactics\nproblem usa1972_p3 (n : ℕ) (digits : DigitSeq n) :\n  (unifDistN n).toOuterMeasure good_seqs = solution n := by\n```\n\nWe need to compute the probability of a good sequence and show it equals the given solution.\n\nTo compute the probability of a good sequence:\n- A good sequence must have at least one even digit (2, 4, 6, 8) and at least one 5\n- The probability of a digit being even is 4/9\n- The probability of a digit being 5 is 1/9\n- The probability of a digit not being even is 5/9\n- The probability of a digit not being 5 is 8/9\n\nThe probability that none of the digits is even is (5/9)^n\nThe probability that none of the digits is 5 is (8/9)^n\n\nThe probability that none of the digits is even or none of the digits is 5 is (5/9)^n + (8/9)^n - (5/9)^n * (8/9)^n\n\nTherefore, the probability that the product is divisible by 10 is 1 - (5/9)^n - (8/9)^n + (5/9)^n * (8/9)^n = 1 - (8/9)^n - (5/9)^n + (4/9)^n\n\nTo prove this in Lean 4:\n\n```tactics\nhave h1 : (unifDistN n).toOuterMeasure good_seqs = solution n := by\n```\n\nWe need to compute the probability of a good sequence and show it equals the given solution.\n\n```tactics\nrw [solution]\n```\n\nNow we need to show that the probability of a good sequence is equal to the given formula.\n\n```tactics\nhave h2 : (unifDistN n).toOuterMeasure good_seqs = 1 - (8 / 9 : ENNReal) ^ n - (5 / 9 : ENNReal) ^ n + (4 / 9 : ENNReal) ^ n := by\n```\n\nTo compute this probability, we need to:\n1. Express the set of good sequences as the union of two independent events\n2. Apply the formula for the union of two independent events: P(A ∪ B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A ∩ B)\n3. Compute each probability\n4. Simplify to the given formula\n\nLet's continue with the proof.\n\n```tactics\nhave h3 : (unifDistN n).toOuterMeasure good_seqs = (unifDistN n).probability (is_good_seq) := by\n  simp [good_seqs]\n```\n\nThe probability of the set of good sequences is the probability of a sequence being good.\n\n```tactics\nrw [h3]\n```\n\nNow we need to compute the probability of a good sequence.\n\n```tactics\nhave h4 : (unifDistN n).probability (is_good_seq) = (1 - (8 / 9 : ENNReal) ^ n - (5 / 9 : ENNReal) ^ n + (4 / 9 : ENNReal) ^ n) := by\n```\n\nTo compute the probability, we need to:\n1. Show that the probability of a good sequence is the probability of having at least one even digit and at least one 5\n2. Compute the probability of having at least one even digit: 1 - probability of no even digits = 1 - (5/9)^n\n3. Compute the probability of having at least one 5: 1 - probability of no 5s = 1 - (8/9)^n\n4. The probability of both is (1 - (5/9)^n) * (1 - (8/9)^n) = 1 - (5/9)^n - (8/9)^n + (5/9)^n * (8/9)^n\n5. Simplify to the given formula\n\nLet's complete the proof.\n\n```tactics\nhave h5 : (unifDistN n).probability (is_good_seq) = (unifDistN n).probability (fun s => 10 ∣ ∏a, to_nat_digit (s a)) := by\n  congr\n```\n\nWe're rewriting the probability of being a good sequence as the probability of the product being divisible by 10.\n\n```tactics\n<;> aesop\n```\n\nThis congruence simplifies the goal.\n\n```tactics\nrw [h5]\n```\n\nNow we need to compute the probability of the product being divisible by 10.\n\n```tactics\nhave h6 : (unifDistN n).probability (fun s => 10 ∣ ∏a, to_nat_digit (s a)) = 1 - (8 / 9 : ENNReal) ^ n - (5 / 9 : ENNReal) ^ n + (4 / 9 : ENNReal) ^ n := by\n```\n\nTo compute this probability, we need to:\n1. Show that the probability of the product being divisible by 10 is the probability of having at least one even digit and at least one 5\n2. Compute the probability of having at least one even digit: 1 - probability of no even digits = 1 - (5/9)^n\n3. Compute the probability of having at least one 5: 1 - probability of no 5s = 1 - (8/9)^n\n4. The probability of both is (1 - (5/9)^n) * (1 - (8/9)^n) = 1 - (5/9)^n - (8/9)^n + (5/9)^n * (8/9)^n\n5. Simplify to the given formula\n\n```tactics\nhave h7 : (unifDistN n).probability (fun s => 10 ∣ ∏a, to_nat_digit (s a)) = (unifDistN n).probability (fun s => (∃ a, (s a = 2 ∨ s a = 4 ∨ s a = 6 ∨ s a = 8)) ∧ (∃ a, (s a = 5))) := by\n```\n\nWe're showing that the probability of the product being divisible by 10 is the probability of having at least one even digit and at least one 5.\n\n```tactics\nhave h8 : ∀ s : DigitSeq n, 10 ∣ ∏a, to_nat_digit (s a) ↔ (∃ a, (s a = 2 ∨ s a = 4 ∨ s a = 6 ∨ s a = 8)) ∧ (∃ a, (s a = 5)) := by\n  intro s\n  simp [to_nat_digit]\n  constructor\n  · -- Assume 10 divides the product\n    intro h\n```\n\nWe need to show that if 10 divides the product, then there's at least one even digit and at least one 5.\n\n```tactics\nhave h2 : ∏a : Fin n, (s a + 1) % 9 = 0 := by\n  omega\n```\n\nThe product is divisible by 10, so it's divisible by 2 and 5.\n\n```tactics\nhave h3 : ∃ a, (s a + 1) % 9 = 2 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 4 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 6 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 8 := by\n  have h4 : 2 ∣ ∏a : Fin n, (s a + 1) := by\n    omega\n```\n\nIf the product is divisible by 2, then there's at least one even digit.\n\n```tactics\nhave h5 : ∃ a, (s a + 1) % 9 = 2 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 4 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 6 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 8 := by\n  by_contra h\n  push_neg at h\n```\n\nIf there's no even digit, then all digits are odd, so the product is odd, which contradicts divisibility by 2.\n\n```tactics\nhave h6 : ∀ a : Fin n, (s a + 1) % 9 = 1 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 3 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 5 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 7 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 9 := by\n  intro a\n  have h7 : (s a + 1) % 9 ≠ 2 ∧ (s a + 1) % 9 ≠ 4 ∧ (s a + 1) % 9 ≠ 6 ∧ (s a + 1) % 9 ≠ 8 := by\n    tauto\n```\n\nIf there's no even digit, then all digits are odd.\n\n```tactics\nhave h8 : (s a + 1) % 9 = 1 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 3 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 5 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 7 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 9 := by\n  omega\n```\n\nThe digit is odd.\n\n```tactics\nassumption\n```\n\nNow we can derive a contradiction with the divisibility by 2.\n\n```tactics\nhave h7 : ¬ (2 ∣ ∏a : Fin n, (s a + 1)) := by\n  have h8 : ∀ a : Fin n, (s a + 1) % 9 = 1 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 3 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 5 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 7 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 9 := by\n    intro a\n    apply h6 a\n```\n\nAll digits are odd.\n\n```tactics\nhave h9 : ¬ (2 ∣ ∏a : Fin n, (s a + 1)) := by\n  apply Nat.not_dvd_of_dvd_of_dvd\n  · -- Show that 2 does not divide any digit\n    intro h\n    obtain ⟨a, ha⟩ := h\n```\n\nIf any digit is even, then the product is even. But we assumed none are even.\n\n```tactics\nhave h10 : (s a + 1) % 9 = 1 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 3 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 5 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 7 ∨ (s a + 1) % 9 = 9 := by\n  apply h6 a\n```\n\nThe digit is odd.\n\n```tactics\nomega\n```\n\nThe digit is odd, so it's not divisible by 2.\n\n```tactics\n· -- Show that 2 divides the product\n  intro h\n  tauto\n```\n\nThis is a contradiction.\n\n```tactics\ncontradiction\n```\n\nSo there must be at least one even digit.\n\n```tactics\nassumption\n```\n\nNow we need to show there's at least one 5.\n\n```tactics\nhave h4 : 5 ∣ ∏a : Fin n, (s a + 1) := by\n  omega\n```\n\nThe product is divisible by 5.\n\n```tactics\nhave h5 : ∃ a, (s a + 1) % 9 = 5 := by\n  by_contra h\n  push_neg at h\n```\n\nIf there's no 5, then none of the digits is 5.\n\n```tactics\nhave h6 : ∀ a : Fin n, (s a + 1) % 9 ≠ 5 := by\n  intro a\n  have h7 : (s a + 1) % 9 ≠ 5 := by\n    tauto\n```\n\nThe digit is not 5.\n\n```tactics\nassumption\n```\n\nNow we can derive a contradiction with the divisibility by 5.\n\n```tactics\nhave h7 : ¬ (5 ∣ ∏a : Fin n, (s a + 1)) := by\n  have h8 : ∀ a : Fin n, (s a + 1) % 9 ≠ 5 := by\n    intro a\n    apply h6 a\n```\n\nNone of the digits is 5.\n\n```tactics\nhave h9 : ¬ (5 ∣ ∏a : Fin n, (s a + 1)) := by\n  apply Nat.not_dvd_of_dvd_of_dvd\n  · -- Show that 5 does not divide any digit\n    intro h\n    obtain ⟨a, ha⟩ := h\n```\n\nIf any digit is 5, then the product is divisible by 5. But we assumed none are 5.\n\n```tactics\nhave h10 : (s a + 1) % 9 ≠ 5 := by\n  apply h6 a\n```\n\nThe digit is not 5.\n\n```tactics\nomega\n```\n\nThe digit is not 5, so it's not divisible by 5.\n\n```tactics\n· -- Show that 5 divides the product\n  intro h\n  tauto\n```\n\nThis is a contradiction.\n\n```tactics\ncontradiction\n```\n\nSo there must be at least one 5.\n\n```tactics\nassumption\n```\n\nWe've shown that if the product is divisible by 10, then there's at least one even digit and at least one 5.\n\n```tactics\n· -- Assume there's at least one even digit and at least one 5\n  rintro ⟨⟨a, ha⟩, ⟨b, hb⟩⟩\n```\n\nWe need to show the product is divisible by 10.\n\n```tactics\nhave h2 : 2 ∣ ∏a : Fin n, (s a + 1) := by\n```\n\nTo show divisibility by 10, we need divisibility by 2 and 5.\n\n```tactics\nhave h3 : ∃ c, (s c + 1) % 9 = 2 ∨ (s c + 1) % 9 = 4 ∨ (s c + 1) % 9 = 6 ∨ (s c + 1) % 9 = 8 := by\n  have h4 : ∃ c, (s c = 2 ∨ s c = 4 ∨ s c = 6 ∨ s c = 8) := by\n    simpa using ha\n```\n\nThere's at least one even digit.\n\n```tactics\nrcases h4 with ⟨c, hc⟩\n```\n\nThe digit is even.\n\n```tactics\nrefine ⟨c, by omega⟩\n```\n\nThe digit is even, so the product is even.\n\n```tactics\nhave h4 : 2 ∣ ∏a : Fin n, (s a + 1) := by\n  apply Finset.dvd_prod_of_mem\n  · -- Show that 2 divides some digit\n    obtain ⟨c, hc⟩ := h3\n```\n\nThe digit is even.\n\n```tactics\nsimp [hc]\n```\n\nThe digit is even, so 2 divides it.\n\n```tactics\n· -- Show that 2 divides the product\n  intro h\n  tauto\n```\n\nThe digit is even, so 2 divides the product.\n\n```tactics\nassumption\n```\n\nNow we need to show divisibility by 5.\n\n```tactics\nhave h3 : 5 ∣ ∏a : Fin n, (s a + 1) := by\n```\n\nTo show divisibility by 5, we need at least one digit divisible by 5.\n\n```tactics\nhave h4 : ∃ c, (s c = 5) := by\n  simpa using hb\n```\n\nThere's at least one 5.\n\n```tactics\nrcases h4 with ⟨c, hc⟩\n```\n\nThe digit is 5.\n\n```tactics\nrefine ⟨c, by omega⟩\n```\n\nThe digit is 5, so 5 divides it.\n