Each digit is independent, with distribution [1/9 for each digit]. The probability that a sequence is good is the probability that there's at least one even digit and at least one 5.

So, using inclusion-exclusion:

P(good) = P(at least one even and at least one 5)
= 1 - P(no evens) - P(no 5s) + P(no evens and no 5s)

P(no evens) = probability all digits are odd. There are 5 odd digits (1, 3, 5, 7, 9). So probability is (5/9)^n.

P(no 5s) = probability that none of the digits is 5. There are 8 digits that are not 5 (since 5 is excluded). So probability is (8/9)^n.

P(no evens and no 5s) = probability that all digits are neither even nor 5. The digits must be from {1, 3, 7, 9}. There are 4 such digits. So probability is (4/9)^n.

Therefore, P(good) = 1 - (5/9)^n - (8/9)^n + (4/9)^n, which is the given solution.

